Abstract
Diabetic retinopathy (DR) is a leading cause of vision impairment worldwide, and automated grading systems play a crucial role in large-scale screening programs. However, deep learning models often exhibit degraded performance when deployed across datasets acquired under different imaging conditions. This study presents a robust dual-resolution deep learning framework for DR grading that integrates attention-based feature fusion with ordinal regression to improve cross-dataset generalization. The proposed method employs two parallel EfficientNet backbones operating at different spatial resolutions to capture complementary retinal features. A learnable attention mechanism adaptively fuses multi-resolution representations, while an ordinal regression formulation based on the cumulative link model (CORAL) explicitly accounts for the ordered nature of DR severity levels. To mitigate domain discrepancies between datasets, a preprocessing strategy combining circular cropping, contrast enhancement, and histogram matching is applied. The model was trained on the APTOS 2019 dataset and evaluated on both an internal validation split and an external Messidor-2 test set. Experimental results demonstrate strong grading performance, achieving a quadratic weighted kappa (QWK) of 0.88 on the APTOS validation set and 0.68 on the unseen Messidor-2 dataset, indicating improved robustness for cross-dataset DR grading applications.

Keywords: diabetic retinopathy; deep learning; convolutional neural networks; ordinal regression; attention mechanism; cross-dataset generalization.

1Introduction
Diabetic Retinopathy (DR) is a diabetic eye disease that is a complication of diabetes. High insulin levels that are connected to diabetes strain the eye blood vessels. Slowly it progresses, and most cases have no particular signs in the early stages. Within the course of the DR progress, vision deteriorates and an individual can have a blurry view, distorted clarity of vision, shadows or spots in their field of view, poor night vision, and shades of color disappear (Siddharth et al., 2022a). As DR progresses, it may evolve into permanent blindness, hence it is a big concern in diabetes management (Bhavya, 2022). The early detection of DR along with other threats is an important part of effective treatment of diabetes complications, and this is supported by several studies (14).

Diabetes afflicted an alarming 463 million people worldwide in 2019, with developing countries like China and India showing a significant increase (Pradeepa and Mohan, 2021; Saeedi et al., 2019). This worrisome tendency is expected to persist, with projections showing that China and India will have the largest burden by 2045 (20). In addition, the risk of diabetes is higher among males (9%) compared to females (7.9%) (Kartha et al., 2017).

Diabetic retinopathy, its ocular presentation, mainly attacks the fragile retina that is damaged and changes its vessels due to increased sugar levels in the blood (Sallam, 2014). Such fluid may result in loss of vision permanently (Abramoff et al., 2018). The magnitude of individuals across the world who develop DR is 30% (20). Early detection and timely treatment are important in avoiding permanent vision loss as DR progresses (Yadav et al., 2021).

Two main variants of DR exist: NPDR (Non-Proliferative Diabetic Retinopathy) and PDR (Proliferative Diabetic Retinopathy). The former is defined by microaneurysms and exudates (Salmon, 2019). DR is characterized by a silent onset. Routine retinal screening continues to be a foundation for early DR detection. Standardly, ophthalmologists use manual grading that involves pupil dilation, specialized lenses, and deep knowledge for an accurate diagnosis (Memari et al., 2020). However, this method presents several drawbacks: dilatation of the pupil is an uncomfortable process requiring specialized equipment, and manual grading tasks require a substantial amount of time and skill, which can tax resources in high-throughput healthcare settings.

These limitations triggered the research for automated and highly user-friendly alternatives. Healthcare technology has led to the emergence of CAD (Computer-Aided Diagnosis) systems, which are an important tool in DR diagnosis (Memari et al., 2020). AI and its subfield, Deep Learning (DL), have brought revolutionary tools for medical image analysis and processing (Davenport and Kalakota, 2019; Liu et al., 2021). DL uses complex multi-layered neural networks to extract subtle patterns from data, significantly increasing its ability to detect diseases such as DR (Chen et al., 2020).

While binary classification focuses on simply categorizing retinas in color fundus images as healthy or diseased (Adriman et al., 2021; Ramchandre et al., 2020), multiclass approaches delve deeper, offering information on five distinct categories: no DR, mild DR, moderate DR, severe DR, and proliferative DR. Several publicly available datasets such as DRIVE, STARE, EyePACS, ROC, and Messidor have been instrumental in spurring the application of DL approaches for detecting and diagnosing age-related maculopathy (Mateen et al., 2020; Voets et al., 2019b; Niemeijer et al., 2010).

Deep learning has significantly advanced automated DR detection and grading. CNNs have been widely used to extract retinal features and classify severity, with recent studies reporting strong results for clinical screening applications (Karthik et al., 2025a). However, conventional CNNs often fail to generalize across datasets with different imaging conditions. Variations in lighting, color, and field of view create domain shift, which limits real-world deployment. To address this, researchers have explored hybrid CNN-transformer models and attention-based architectures that improve feature discrimination and capture multi-scale information. Preprocessing techniques such as histogram matching and contrast enhancement have also been proposed to reduce dataset discrepancies (Bappi et al., 2025a).

Despite these advances, existing approaches often rely on single-resolution inputs or lack explicit mechanisms to fuse complementary information from multiple spatial scales. Moreover, few studies systematically evaluate model generalization across external datasets, which is essential for assessing clinical robustness. To overcome these limitations, we propose a dual-resolution, attention-based deep learning framework that integrates multi-scale retinal features and employs an ordinal regression loss to respect the ordered severity structure inherent in DR grading. The model incorporates data preprocessing and domain adaptation techniques to reduce inter-dataset variability and is evaluated using both internal validation and external testing on independent retinal image collections.

Deep learning, especially convolutional neural networks, has become the go-to approach for automating DR detection and grading from fundus images. Multiple studies have shown that these models consistently outperform traditional machine learning methods because they can learn hierarchical retinal features closely tied to disease progression (Gulshan et al., 2016; Karthik et al., 2025a). That said, high accuracy on the training dataset does not always translate to real-world performance. Many models see a noticeable drop in robustness when tested on images from different sources, pointing to ongoing challenges with domain shift and generalization (Bappi et al., 2025a).

Mohanty et al. (2023) propose two deep learning architectures — a hybrid network composed of VGG16 and XGBoost Classifier, and a DenseNet-121 network — for the diagnosis and determination of DR. The hybrid network achieved 79.50% accuracy and the DenseNet-121 model achieved the highest accuracy of 97.30% using the APTOS 2019 dataset. Raiaan et al. (2023) target the identification and classification of fundus photos into five DR classes, producing the RetNet-10 model giving 98.65% accuracy. Nivedha and Sreelakshmi (2023) introduces a deep learning method with MobileNetV2 for DR detection achieving approximately 85.28% classification accuracy. Another study (Raman and Nishanthi, 2023) developed an EfficientNet-B7 model to detect DR using the APTOS 2019 dataset, achieving 94% accuracy.

Mondal et al. (2023) developed a deep learning framework named EDLDR as an ensemble method for DR diagnosis and classification using retinal fundus images, achieving an accuracy of 86.08% for five classes and 96.98% for two classes. Nazir et al. (2021) propose a new method based on a custom deep learning CenterNet model tested on APTOS-2019 and IDRiD datasets with average accuracies of 97.93% and 98.10%, respectively. Subbanna (2023) suggests a deep learning method with the CNN architecture and MobileNetV2 attaining 92.6% accuracy. Abirami and Kavitha (2022) proposes an ensemble model based on EfficientNet achieving a 0.907 quadratic weighted kappa score on an independent test dataset.

Recent work has shown that combining transfer learning with attention mechanisms can be highly effective for ocular disease classification (Fu et al., 2024a). DR presents a particular challenge because lesions come in different sizes and have varied visual characteristics. This has led many researchers to explore multi-scale CNN architectures that can capture both small lesion details and larger retinal patterns. Fu et al. (2024a) proposed a multi-scale EfficientNet framework that fuses features from different receptive fields and showed improved severity grading. Shakibania et al. (2024a) took a similar approach with a dual-branch network and found that parallel feature extraction outperforms single-stream designs.

Attention mechanisms have become increasingly common in DR analysis because they help highlight the regions that matter most — areas with microaneurysms, hemorrhages, and other pathological features (Romero-Oraa et al., 2024a). More recent approaches use channel-wise or spatial attention to weight features more selectively, leading to better and more consistent grading results (Zhang et al., 2025). It is also worth noting that DR grading is not a standard classification problem. Ordinal regression methods like CORAL address this by enforcing rank consistency, which tends to improve agreement metrics like quadratic weighted kappa (Shi et al., 2023). Several DR studies have highlighted how ordinal-aware approaches and QWK-based evaluation better reflect clinical grading behavior (Karthik et al., 2025a; Chilukoti et al., 2024).

One issue affecting many DR grading systems is their dependence on dataset-specific characteristics (Bappi et al., 2025a). To deal with this, researchers have turned to preprocessing techniques like circular cropping, contrast enhancement, and histogram alignment (Fu et al., 2024a; Romero-Oraa et al., 2024a). Taking all of this into account, the present work brings together several directions from the literature: dual-resolution feature extraction (Fu et al., 2024a; Shakibania et al., 2024a), attention-based fusion (Romero-Oraa et al., 2024a; Zhang et al., 2025), ordinal regression via CORAL (Shi et al., 2023; Chilukoti et al., 2024), and cross-dataset evaluation to address domain shift (Bappi et al., 2025a). The proposed model is tested on the Messidor-2 dataset to assess its generalization ability.

2Materials and Methods
The proposed methodology addresses automated DR grading by combining dual-resolution retinal feature extraction, attention-based feature fusion, and ordinal regression modeling, with explicit consideration of cross-dataset robustness. The framework is designed to capture complementary retinal patterns at different spatial scales while respecting the ordinal nature of DR severity levels and mitigating domain shift between heterogeneous datasets. The workflow consists of the following steps: (1) dataset preparation and splitting, (2) preprocessing and domain normalization, (3) dual-resolution feature extraction, (4) attention-guided feature fusion, (5) ordinal regression using CORAL loss, and (6) training and evaluation with internal and external validation.

2.1Dataset Preparation and Splitting
Two publicly available collections of retinal fundus images were used in this study: APTOS 2019 and Messidor-2. APTOS 2019 (4) served as the main dataset for training and internal validation. Each image in this dataset comes with a label indicating the severity of diabetic retinopathy, ranging from 0 (no disease) to 4 (proliferative DR, the most advanced stage), as shown in Figure 1. The dataset was divided into training and validation portions using stratified sampling, which ensures both portions have a similar balance of severity levels.

