Messidor-2 (Decenciere et al., 2014) consists of retinal fundus images collected from multiple clinical centres using different acquisition devices, resulting in substantial variability in illumination, colour distribution, and field of view. Each image is labelled with a DR severity grade consistent with the same five-level ordinal scale used in APTOS. For the Messidor-2 dataset, only images marked as gradable and adjudicated were included to ensure reliable evaluation. This dataset was split into: (a) a training portion, which was included so the model could learn from images captured under different conditions and equipment; and (b) a test portion, which was kept completely separate and only used for final evaluation. The final training set was created by combining the APTOS 2019 training samples with the Messidor-2 training portion.

2.2Preprocessing and Domain Normalization
Retinal fundus images can look quite different from one another depending on the camera used, lighting conditions, and how much of the eye was captured. To handle this variability and make the model more reliable, a series of preprocessing steps were applied to all images.

Retinal Region Isolation.
Each image was cropped in a circular shape to remove the dark, uninformative background around the edges. This keeps only the actual retinal area and removes distracting artefacts near the borders, also helping ensure that all images have a consistent spatial layout.

Dataset-Aware Image Enhancement.
Two different enhancement techniques were used to bring out different visual features:

• Ben Graham normalisation highlights blood vessel structures and improves overall contrast. It was originally introduced during the Kaggle Diabetic Retinopathy Detection competition and has since become a standard preprocessing step for fundus images (Graham,).
• Contrast-Limited Adaptive Histogram Equalisation (CLAHE) boosts local contrast, making it easier to spot small lesions and subtle abnormalities that might otherwise go unnoticed (Zuiderveld, 1994). Each enhanced version captures different but useful information, so both are fed into separate branches of the network.
Histogram Matching for Domain Alignment.
Images from APTOS 2019 and Messidor-2 often have noticeable differences in colour and brightness. To reduce this gap, histogram matching was applied to the Messidor-2 images. A reference image from the APTOS training set was selected, and the colour and intensity distribution of each Messidor-2 image was adjusted to match it. This brings the two datasets closer together statistically without changing the actual medical content of the images (Gonzalez and Woods, 2018). All preprocessing stages are illustrated in Figure 2 using representative samples from both datasets.

