3.4Summary of Quantitative Results
To summarize: training loss decreased steadily across epochs (CORAL loss); APTOS validation QWK: 0.88; Messidor-2 external test QWK: 0.68. These results show that the model performs well on in-domain data and maintains reasonable robustness when applied to an external dataset under realistic conditions.

4Discussion
4.1Effect of Ordinal Loss Optimization
The choice of CORAL loss had a significant impact on how the model learned to grade DR severity. Unlike standard categorical cross-entropy, which treats all misclassifications equally, CORAL explicitly accounts for the ordering of severity levels and penalizes large ranking errors more heavily. This difference shows up clearly in the confusion matrices, where most misclassifications stay within neighbouring grades rather than jumping across multiple levels. This kind of behaviour is exactly what one would want in a clinical grading system. These findings align with earlier studies that have highlighted the value of ordinal modelling for tasks like DR severity assessment (Cao et al., 2020a; Karthik et al., 2025b).

4.2Dual Preprocessing and Feature Fusion
The decision to use two preprocessing pipelines — Ben Graham normalisation and CLAHE — allowed the model to learn from complementary views of the same retinal image. Each preprocessing method emphasizes different aspects of the fundus image, and combining them gives the model access to a richer set of features. The attention-based fusion module takes this a step further by learning to weight features from each branch depending on the input image, which helps when dealing with images that vary in lesion visibility or contrast. This approach builds on recent attention-based DR frameworks but goes a step further by integrating preprocessing diversity directly into the learning pipeline (Bappi et al., 2025b; Siddharth et al., 2022b).

4.3Cross-Dataset Generalization
The drop in performance between APTOS and Messidor-2 is a reminder of how challenging domain shift remains in retinal imaging. Even with histogram matching applied and some Messidor-2 images included during training, the model still performed noticeably better on in-domain data than on the external test set. This pattern is consistent with what other recent cross-dataset DR studies have reported (Romero-Oraa et al., 2024b; Voets et al., 2019a; Fu et al., 2024b). It is worth noting that the evaluation protocol used here is stricter than what many prior studies have adopted.

