4.5Limitations
The model was trained using image-level labels only, since lesion-level annotations were not available in the datasets used. Exploring weakly-supervised methods to bring in finer-grained supervision could be a useful next step. Although histogram matching helped reduce the gap between datasets, more advanced domain adaptation techniques such as adversarial training were not used, and these might push cross-dataset performance even further. Finally, the model was only tested on two public datasets — APTOS and Messidor-2. To really know how well this approach holds up in practice, it would need to be validated on clinical data from multiple centres.

5Conclusions
This work presented a hybrid dual-branch framework for DR grading that brings together three key components: dual preprocessing, attention-based feature fusion, and CORAL ordinal regression. The model achieved strong in-domain performance on APTOS, reaching a QWK of 0.88, and showed reasonable generalization on the external Messidor-2 dataset with a QWK of 0.68, all under a strict evaluation protocol that kept training and test data fully separate. The findings reinforce the value of ordinal-aware loss functions and multi-resolution feature integration for severity grading in DR. At the same time, the performance gap between datasets serves as a reminder that domain shift remains a significant hurdle in retinal imaging.

Looking ahead, there are several directions worth exploring. Stronger domain adaptation methods could help close the gap between training and external performance. Incorporating lesion-level supervision may improve the model’s ability to capture fine-grained pathology. And validation on larger, multi-centre datasets would provide a clearer picture of how the approach performs across diverse clinical settings.

